{
  "text": "British Journal of Cancer (2001) Previous epidemiological studies showed inconsistent results for the association between fish consumption and risk of lung cancer. A study in Norway found a negative association between cod liver oil supplement and lung cancer risk, due to high intake of vitamin A and n-3 PUFA [CITATION_1] . A decreased OR was observed in female nonsmokers of Hong Kong [CITATION_2] and in males of Australia [CITATION_3] , although the numbers of cases were small. On the other hand, fish consumption was associated with increased OR for lung cancer in males of Yunnan, China, where average consumption of fish in controls was very low [CITATION_4] . Moreover, 2 cohort and 2 casecontrol studies found no association [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Fish consumption was, however, inversely associated with male lung cancer mortality in countries with high levels of cigarette smoking or animal fat consumption in a recent ecological study [CITATION_9] . Of 36 countries, Japan with lower mortality rate of lung cancer showed higher consumption of cigarette smoking and fish, but lower animal fat intake.",
